intent: >
  Introduce the Site model — the data shape every Epic 1 slice builds on.
  Codifies URL format, interval floor, and the unknown/up/down status enum.

slice: 1/8
kind: feature
behavior_change: additive

reversibility: entangled
# Adds a migration + new table. `git revert` alone won't drop the sites
# table — a rollback needs a down migration or manual DROP TABLE.

scope:
  declared:
    - app/models/site.rb
    - db/migrate/*_create_sites.rb
    - db/schema.rb
    - spec/models/site_spec.rb
  actual:
    - app/models/site.rb
    - db/migrate/20260411235013_create_sites.rb
    - db/schema.rb
    - spec/models/site_spec.rb
  drift: []

proof:
  tests_run: bin/dc bundle exec rspec spec/models/site_spec.rb
  result: green
  failing: 0

tests:
  needed: "yes"
  added:
    - spec/models/site_spec.rb

lint:
  run: bin/dc bundle exec rubocop app/models/site.rb spec/models/site_spec.rb db/migrate/20260411235013_create_sites.rb
  result: clean
  count: 0

assumptions:
  - "30s minimum check interval is the right product floor for an MVP (chosen to keep noise down; easy to lower later)."
  - "URI::DEFAULT_PARSER regex is sufficient URL validation for slice 1. It is permissive (accepts http://foo with no TLD). Tightening is deferred to slice 3 where HttpChecker actually fetches."
  - "Default status `:unknown` is the right initial state (as opposed to nil or `unchecked`) — makes the flip-event semantics in slice 4 cleaner."
  - "Plan's slice-1 file list originally omitted db/schema.rb; corrected mid-slice so scope.declared stays honest. Any migration slice implicitly touches schema.rb."

deviations_from_plan: none

trade_offs: >
  Chose URI::DEFAULT_PARSER.make_regexp over a hand-rolled host/scheme
  parser because (a) it's stdlib, (b) tightening is a slice-3 problem
  where SSRF risk actually bites, (c) over-validating at the model
  layer would push reviewers to argue about regexes instead of the
  data shape.

self_review:
  error_paths: >
    URL regex is permissive — `http://foo` passes. Conscious punt: the
    fetch layer in slice 3 is where the real validation (resolvable host,
    non-private address, scheme whitelist against SSRF) belongs. Model-
    layer validation is a typo gate, not a security boundary.
  security: >
    Site.url is user-supplied and will be fetched by HttpChecker in slice
    3. SSRF risk (private-range hosts, link-local, cloud metadata endpoints)
    exists but is not addressed at the model. Flag for slice-3 reviewer
    attention — this is where the check belongs.

confidence: high

reviewer_attention:
  - app/models/site.rb:8-11  # URL regex choice — revisit in slice 3
